{{Pfam_box|Symbol=Na_H_Exchanger|Name=Sodium/hydrogen exchanger family|image=1zcd_opm.png|width=|caption=|Pfam=PF00999|InterPro=|SMART=|Prosite=|SCOP=|TCDB=2.A.36|OPM family=106|OPM protein=4bwz|PDB=}}
The '''Monovalent Cation:Proton Antiporter-1 (CPA1) Family''' ([http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.36 TC# 2.A.36]) is a large family of proteins derived from [[Gram-positive bacteria|Gram-positive]] and [[Gram-negative bacteria|Gram-negative]] bacteria, [[Cyanobacteria|blue-green bacteria]], [[archaea]], [[yeast]], [[plant]]s and [[animal]]s. The CPA1 family belongs to the VIC superfamily.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Chang AB, Lin R, Keith Studley W, Tran CV, Saier MH | title = Phylogeny as a guide to structure and function of membrane transport proteins | journal = Molecular Membrane Biology | volume = 21 | issue = 3 | pages = 171–81 | date = 2004-06-01 | pmid = 15204625 | doi = 10.1080/09687680410001720830 }}</ref><ref name=":0">{{cite journal | vauthors = Saier MH, Eng BH, Fard S, Garg J, Haggerty DA, Hutchinson WJ, Jack DL, Lai EC, Liu HJ, Nusinew DP, Omar AM, Pao SS, Paulsen IT, Quan JA, Sliwinski M, Tseng TT, Wachi S, Young GB | title = Phylogenetic characterization of novel transport protein families revealed by genome analyses | journal = Biochimica et Biophysica Acta | volume = 1422 | issue = 1 | pages = 1–56 | date = February 1999 | pmid = 10082980 | doi = 10.1016/s0304-4157(98)00023-9 }}</ref> Transporters from eukaryotes have been functionally characterized to catalyze Na<sup>+</sup>:H<sup>+</sup> exchange. Their primary physiological functions are thought to be in (1) cytoplasmic pH regulation, extruding the H<sup>+</sup> generated during metabolism, and (2) salt tolerance (in plants), due to Na<sup>+</sup> uptake into vacuoles. Bacterial homologues have also been found to facilitate Na<sup>+</sup>:H<sup>+</sup> [[Antiporter|antiport]], but some also catalyze Li<sup>+</sup>:H<sup>+</sup> antiport or Ca<sup>2+</sup>:H<sup>+</sup> antiport under certain conditions.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Waditee R, Hibino T, Tanaka Y, Nakamura T, Incharoensakdi A, Takabe T | title = Halotolerant cyanobacterium Aphanothece halophytica contains an Na(+)/H(+) antiporter, homologous to eukaryotic ones, with novel ion specificity affected by C-terminal tail | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 276 | issue = 40 | pages = 36931–8 | date = October 2001 | pmid = 11479290 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M103650200 }}</ref>

== Phylogeny ==
The [[phylogenetic tree]] for the CPA1 family shows three principal clusters. The first cluster includes proteins derived exclusively from animals, and all of the functionally characterized members of the family belong to this cluster. Of the two remaining clusters, one includes all bacterial homologues while the other includes one from ''[[Arabidopsis thaliana]],'' one from ''[[Homo sapiens]]'' and two from yeast (''[[Saccharomyces cerevisiae|S. cerevisiae]]'' and ''[[Schizosaccharomyces pombe|S. pombe]]''). Several organisms possess multiple paralogues; for example, seven paralogues are found in ''[[Caenorhabditis elegans|C. elegans]],'' and five are known in humans. Most of these paralogues are very similar in sequence, and they belong to the animal specific cluster.<ref name=":0" />

A representative list of proteins belonging to the CPA1 family can be found in the [http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.36.8 Transporter Classification Database].

== Structure ==
Numerous members of the CPA1 family have been sequenced, and these proteins vary substantially in size. The bacterial proteins have 520-550 amino acyl residues (aas) while eukaryotic proteins are generally larger, varying in size from 540-900 residues. They exhibit 10-12 putative transmembrane α-helical spanners (TMSs). A proposed [[Topology|topological]] model suggests that in addition to 12 TMSs, a region between TMSs 9 and 10 dips into the membrane to line the pore. However, one homologue, Nhx1 of ''[[Saccharomyces cerevisiae|S. cerevisiae]]'' ([http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.36.1.12 TC# 2.A.36.1.12])'','' has an extracellular glycosylated C-terminus.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wakabayashi S, Pang T, Su X, Shigekawa M | title = A novel topology model of the human Na(+)/H(+) exchanger isoform 1 | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 275 | issue = 11 | pages = 7942–9 | date = March 2000 | pmid = 10713111 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.275.11.7942 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wells KM, Rao R | title = The yeast Na+/H+ exchanger Nhx1 is an N-linked glycoprotein. Topological implications | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 276 | issue = 5 | pages = 3401–7 | date = February 2001 | pmid = 11036065 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M001688200 }}</ref>

== Function ==
Using the mammalian NHE1 ([http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.36.1.1 TC# 2.A.36.1.1]), it has been found that TMSs 4 and 9 as well as the extracellular loop between TMSs 3 and 4 are important for drug ([[amiloride]]- and [[benzoyl]] [[Guanidine|guanidinium]]-based derivatives) sensitivities. Mutations in these regions also affect transport activities. M4 and M9 therefore contain critical sites for both drug and [[cation]] recognition.

=== Transport Reaction ===
The generalized transport reaction catalyzed by functionally characterized members of the CPA1 family is:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.36|title=2.A.36 The Monovalent Cation:Proton Antiporter-1 (CPA1) Family|website=Transporter Classification Database|access-date=2016-03-16}}</ref><blockquote>Na<sup>+</sup> (out) + H<sup>+</sup> (in) ⇌ Na<sup>+</sup> (in) + H<sup>+</sup> (out).</blockquote>

