{{More footnotes|date=May 2016}}

A '''Merodiploid''' is a partially diploid bacterium, which has its own [[chromosome]] complement and a chromosome fragment introduced by [[Conjugation (acid-base theory)|conjugation]], transformation or [[transduction (genetics)|transduction]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=merodiploid|url=http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/merodiploid|journal=The Free Dictionary|accessdate=2016-05-13}}</ref> It can also be defined as an essentially haploid [[organism]] that carries a second copy of a part of its genome. The term is derived from the Greek, meros = part, and was originally used to describe both unstable partial diploidy, such as that which occurs briefly in recipients after mating with an Hfr strain (1), and the stable state, exemplified by F-prime strains (see Hfr'S And F-Primes). Over time the usage has tended to confine the term to descriptions of stable genetic states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://what-when-how.com/molecular-biology/merodiploids-molecular-biology/|title=Merodiploids (Molecular Biology)|website=What-when-how.com|accessdate=2016-05-13}}</ref> '''Merodiploidy''' refers to the partial duplication of chromosomes in a haploid organism.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Natural Genetic Transformation Generates a Population of Merodiploids in Streptococcus pneumoniae|first1=Calum |last1= Johnston |first2=Stéphanie |last2=Caymaris |first3=Aldert |last3=Zomer|first4=Hester J. |last4=Bootsma|first5=Marc |last5=Prudhomme|first6=Chantal |last6=Granadel|first7= Peter W. M. |last7=Hermans|first8=Patrice |last8=Polard|first9=Bernard |last9=Martin|first10=Jean-Pierre |last10=Claverys|journal=PLOS Genetics|date=26 September 2013|volume=9|issue=9|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosgenetics/article?id=10.1371/journal.pgen.1003819}}</ref>

